'''Jeffrey Baena''' (June 29, 1977 – January 3, 2025) was an American screenwriter and film director. He wrote and directed ''[[Life After Beth]]'' (2014), ''[[Joshy]]'' (2016), ''[[The Little Hours]]'' (2017), ''[[Horse Girl]]'' (2020) and ''[[Spin Me Round]]'' (2022) and co-wrote ''[[I Heart Huckabees]]'' (2004). He was known for his frequent collaborations with actresses [[Alison Brie]] (with whom he co-wrote ''Horse Girl'' and ''Spin Me Round''), [[Molly Shannon]], and [[Aubrey Plaza]].

== Early life==
Baena was born on June 29, 1977,<ref name="Igoe">{{Cite web |last=Igoe |first=Katherine J. |date=January 17, 2023 |title=Aubrey Plaza's Low-Key Husband Jeff Baena Is So Supportive and Cute |url=https://www.aol.com/aubrey-plazas-low-key-husband-200900350.html |access-date=January 4, 2025 |website=[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]] |language=en-US |via=[[AOL]]}}</ref> and grew up in a [[Jewish secularism|secular Jewish]] family in [[Miami]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Lindner |first=Emmett |date=January 4, 2025 |title=Jeff Baena, Film Director and Screenwriter, Dies at 47 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2025/01/04/arts/jeff-baena-dead.html |url-access=limited |accessdate=January 4, 2025 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Russell |first1=Anna |date=June 26, 2017 |title=Jeff Baena and Aubrey Plaza's Medieval Adventure |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/07/03/jeff-baena-and-aubrey-plazas-medieval-adventure#:~:text=Baena%20grew%20up%20in%20a%20secular%20Jewish%20household%20in%20Miami. |magazine=The New Yorker}}</ref> He graduated from the [[New York University Tisch School of the Arts]] with a degree in film and moved to [[Los Angeles]] to pursue directing.<ref name="bbc">{{cite web |title=Filmmaker Jeff Baena, husband of Aubrey Plaza, dead at 47 |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/articles/cvgny622w0zo |website=BBC |access-date=January 4, 2025 |date=January 4, 2025}}</ref>

== Career ==
Baena became a production assistant for filmmaker [[Robert Zemeckis]] on ''[[What Lies Beneath]]'' and ''[[Cast Away]]'' (both 2000).<ref name="Zax">{{Cite news |last=Zax |first=David |date=February 3, 2016 |title=How A Freak Eye Injury Became A Career Turning Point For The Director Of ''Joshy'' |url=http://www.fastcompany.com/3056144/most-creative-people/how-a-freak-eye-injury-became-a-career-turning-point-for-the-director-o |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20161003150842/https://www.fastcompany.com/3056144/most-creative-people/how-a-freak-eye-injury-became-a-career-turning-point-for-the-director-o |archive-date=October 3, 2016 |access-date=February 3, 2016 |work=[[Fast Company]] |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.networkisa.org/creative-screenwriting/view/outline-over-screenplay-jeff-baena-on-spin-me-round-interview|title='Outline Over Screenplay' Jeff Baena On 'Spin Me Round Interview'|date=December 19, 2022|website=International Screenwriters' Association|access-date=January 4, 2025}}</ref> After working with Zemeckis, Baena became an assistant editor for writer-director [[David O. Russell]]. After a year and a half of working together, a minor car accident injured one of Baena's eyes. Partially to keep his spirits up and pass the time during his recovery, Russell began discussing story ideas with Baena. The two ended up collaborating on four scripts together, including ''[[I Heart Huckabees]]'', which Russell directed in 2004, and [[Jay Roach]]'s ''[[Meet the Fockers]]'' (also 2004), for which they made uncredited revisions.<ref name="Zax" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://norman.hrc.utexas.edu/fasearch/findingaid.cfm?eadid=00481&kw=de%20niro|title=Robert De Niro: A Preliminary Inventory of His Papers at the Harry Ransom Center|publisher=[[Harry Ransom Center]]|via=[[University of Texas at Austin]]|access-date=January 4, 2025}}</ref>{{rp|146–147}}

